<li><li>death</li>
<li><li>mocking</li>
<li><li>it is merely a form of rest or sleep</li>
<li><li>it is at the mercy of chance or fate</li>
<li><li>there is no death in heaven</li>
<li><li>having or showing little hope</li>
<li>According to the poet death can destroy body but the soul is immortal.</li>
<li>Death is a source of pleasure as it is merely a form of rest or sleep.</li>
<li>Death is not mighty and dreadful because it is at the mercy of chance or fate.</li>
<li>Poet here means by the immortality of soul as there is no death in heaven.</li>
<li><li>Disperate</li>
<li>Dreadful</li>
</ol>
<p><span style="color: #eb4924;"><strong>Passage 17:</strong></span><br />
Elegy on the death of a mad dog
Good people all, of every sort,<br />
Give ear unto my song;<br />
And if you find it wond'rous short,<br />
<strong>4</strong> It cannot hold you long,<br />
In Islington there was a man,<br />
Of whom the world might say,<br />
That still a godly race he ran,<br />
<strong>8</strong> Whene'er he went to pray.<br />
A kind and gentle heart he had,<br />
To comfort friends and foes;<br />
The naked every day he clad,<br />
<strong>12</strong> When he put on his clothes.<br />
And in that town a dog was found,<br />
As many dogs there be,<br />
But mongrel, puppy, whelp, and hound,<br />
<strong>16</strong> And curs of low degree.<br />
This dog and man at first were friends;<br />
But when a pique began,<br />
The dog, to gain some private ends,<br />
<strong>20</strong> Went mad and bit the man.<br />
Around from all the neighbouring streets<br />
The wond'ring neighbours ran,<br />
And swore the dog had lost his wits,<br />
<strong>24</strong> To bite so good a man.<br />
The wound it seem'd both sore and sad<br />
To every Christian eye:<br />
And while they swore the dog was mad,<br />
<strong>28</strong> The swore the man would die.<br />
But soon a wonder came to light,<br />
That show'd the rogues they lied;<br />
The man recover'd of the bite,<br />
<strong>32</strong> The dog it was that died.<br />
pqro
xproAnswer the following questions by choosing the most appropriate option:
<ol type="a">
<li>The man in Islington seemed to lead a pious and religious life as
<li>he loved dogs and fed them</li>
<li>he was self centred and very busy</li>
<li>he went to pray regularly</li>
<li>he ran charitable trust</li>
</li>
<li>The dog was different from other dogs of the town because
<li>it was not faithful</li>
<li>it was not aggressive</li>
<li>it lacked sensitivity to pain, punishment and rebuke</li>
<li>it had human qualities of love, hate and revenge</li>
</li>
<li>The dog went mad and bit the man because
<li>it had to gain some selfish interests</li>
<li>it was shocked by the selfish attitude of man</li>
<li>the enmity between it and the man unhinged it</li>
<li>it wanted to teach the man a lesson .</li>
</li>
<li>The good people of the town considered the man's wound deplorable because
<li>the mad dog had done something very evil</li>
<li>they foresaw the end of the good man because of the dog bite</li>
<li>the dog bite was unexpected and quite deep</li>
<li>the action of the dog was strange and selfish</li>
</li>
<li>The man recovered of the bite and the dog died because
<li>the man led a religious and pious life</li>
<li>the dog was cruel, ungrateful and selfish</li>
<li>the selfish dissembler was more poisonous than a mad dog</li>
<li>the good dog had to go mad to bite such a kind-hearted man</li>
</li>
<li>The poetic device used in the last stanza of the poem is
<li>simile</li>
<li>metaphor</li>
<li>metonymy</li>
